20. I have a fondness for kobolds, precisely because they're so weak individually. As a referee, it's very satisfying to throw large numbers of them at the characters without (too much) fear that they'll overwhelm them. Conversely, players tend to underestimate them, which can lead them to act foolishly when their character are confronted by them. OD&D provides no description of kobolds, but the 1977 Basic Rules edited by Dr J. Eric Holmes, which was the rulebook from which I first learned to play D&D, describes them as \u8220\'1cevil dwarf-like creatures.\u8221\'1d I remembered this description and }{\i0\ai0\rtlch \ltrch\loch
tied it into the mythology of the dwarves that was evolving through play. I came up with the notion that kobolds were \u8220\'1cfailed\u8221\'1d dwarves, the botched results of dwarven reproduction. I further imagined that they had the ability to transform dead dwarves into more of their own kind, thus explaining the mutual hatred between them and dwarves.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\ql\nowidctlpar\ltrpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\cf0\loch\f3\fs24\lang4105{\i0\ai0\rtlch \ltrch\loch
