As a referee, I find it very easy to keep going back to same well for ideas. That's why I like random tables: they force me to grapple with results I would never come up with on my own. Had it not been for the 2000 copper pieces, }{\i0\ai0\rtlch \ltrch\loch
the spark of some important aspects of my ongoing campaign would never have come to be. It wasn't the only spark, but it played a role. That's one of the lessons I learned early on: you never know what might inspire you. Going into dungeon creation with a \u8220\'1cplan\u8221\'1d or \u8220\'1cvision\u8221\'1d beforehand might appear to lead to a more \u8220\'1ccoherent\u8221\'1d locale. In my experience, though, it made things more predictable and bland. I ended up abandoning many of my initial ideas after better ones emerged through }{\i0\ai0\rtlch \ltrch\loch
